  "Question": "<p>I am looking for a reference to answer the question in the title. Let me try to clarify a little what I mean:</p> <p>If a single sheaf <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_800\"><math alttext=\"\\mathscr{F}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathscript\">\u2131</mi></semantics></math></span> has a resolution <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_801\"><math alttext=\"\\mathscr{G}^{\\bullet}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathscript\">\ud835\udca2</mi><mo>\u2219</mo></msup></semantics></math></span> by not necessarily injective objects, then the usual cohomology of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_802\"><math alttext=\"\\mathscr{F}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathscript\">\u2131</mi></semantics></math></span> is isomorphic to the hypercohomology of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_803\"><math alttext=\"\\mathscr{G}^{\\bullet}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathscript\">\ud835\udca2</mi><mo>\u2219</mo></msup></semantics></math></span>:  <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_804\"><math alttext=\"H^{i}(X,\\mathscr{F})\\cong\\mathbb{H}^{i}(X,\\mathscr{G}^{\\bullet}).\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><msup><mi>H</mi><mi>i</mi></msup><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>,</mo><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathscript\">\u2131</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>\u2245</mo><mrow><msup><mi>\u210d</mi><mi>i</mi></msup><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>,</mo><msup><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathscript\">\ud835\udca2</mi><mo>\u2219</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>.</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>Now, if one was starting with a complex of sheaves <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_805\"><math alttext=\"\\mathscr{F}^{\\bullet}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathscript\">\u2131</mi><mo>\u2219</mo></msup></semantics></math></span> and a \"resolution\" thereof, i.e. a complex of complexes <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_806\"><math alttext=\"(\\mathscr{G}^{\\bullet})^{\\bullet}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathscript\">\ud835\udca2</mi><mo>\u2219</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo>\u2219</mo></msup></semantics></math></span>, then one should touch on a concept that could be called hyper-hypercohomology. </p> <p>Yet, I never heard of its existence and I'm pretty sure it does not give you anything new, as soon as you work in the derived category. I just find myself unable to pin down why exactly this is the case. </p> <p>Any ideas anyone?</p>",
  "Title": "Why is there no hyper-hypercohomology?",
